
Async Job System Platform (Flagship Backend Project)



0) Goal


Build a backend platform that lets you submit work as jobs, processes them asynchronously via workers, and exposes status/results through an API.
It supports multiple job types (CSV processing is the first).




1) Architecture (2 processes, 1 repo)



Processes


1.	API Service (Spring Boot)
o	Receives requests
o	Validates input
o	Creates jobs in storage
o	Exposes endpoints to query jobs and fetch results
2.
3.	Worker Service (Spring Boot or plain JVM app)
o	Polls/claims jobs
o	Executes job handlers by type
o	Updates job state + stores outputs
o	Retries on failure
4.



Shared Infrastructure


•	Database (Postgres recommended; H2 for dev ok)
•	(Optional later) Redis for faster queueing / caching / rate limiting





2) Core Domain Model



Job fields (minimum)


•	id (UUID)
•	type (string/enum: CSV_PROCESS, EMAIL_SEND, REPORT_GENERATE, …)
•	status (enum)
o	QUEUED
o	RUNNING
o	SUCCEEDED
o	FAILED
o	CANCELLED (later)
•
•	attempt (int)
•	maxAttempts (int)
•	priority (int) (later)
•	payload (JSON string) — job input
•	result (JSON string or reference key) — job output
•	error (string) — last error message/stack summary
•	createdAt, updatedAt
•	scheduledFor (timestamp) (later)
•	lockedAt, lockedBy (worker id) — for claiming jobs





3) Job Lifecycle Rules


•	API creates a job with status QUEUED
•	Worker claims a job:
o	atomically sets RUNNING, sets lockedBy, lockedAt
•
•	Worker completes job:
o	set SUCCEEDED and store result
•
•	Worker failure:
o	increment attempt
o	if attempt < maxAttempts: return to QUEUED with backoff delay
o	else: set FAILED and store error
•
•	Job claiming must prevent double-processing (idempotency mindset)





4) Minimum Feature List (MVP)



A) Job API (core platform)


•	POST /jobs → submit a job (generic)
o	body: { "type": "...", "payload": {...}, "maxAttempts": 5 }
o	returns: { "jobId": "...", "status": "QUEUED" }
•
•	GET /jobs/{id} → job status + metadata
•	GET /jobs → list jobs with filters:
o	status, type, createdAfter, createdBefore (basic)
•
•	POST /jobs/{id}/cancel (optional in MVP; easy later)



B) Worker (core platform)


•	Poll loop:
o	every X ms, attempt to claim N jobs
•
•	Job handler dispatch:
o	switch/map from job.type → handler
•
•	Reliable state updates:
o	mark running, store heartbeat timestamp (later)
•
•	Retry + backoff:
o	exponential backoff (simple: 2s, 5s, 15s, 30s, …)
•
•	Dead-letter behavior:
o	once max attempts exceeded → FAILED
•



C) Observability (MVP)


•	Structured logs:
o	job id, job type, status transitions
•
•	Simple metrics endpoint (optional):
o	counts by status/type
•





5) First Job Type: CSV Processing (First “Vehicle”)



Purpose


Prove the platform is useful by supporting a real long-running task.


CSV Processing flow


1.	Client uploads CSV
2.	API stores file (or raw bytes) and creates job CSV_PROCESS
3.	Worker processes:
o	parses
o	validates
o	transforms
o	outputs result file + summary
4.



CSV endpoints (recommended)


•	POST /csv/jobs → upload CSV and create job
o	returns { jobId }
•
•	GET /csv/jobs/{id}/result → download processed output (when succeeded)
•	GET /csv/jobs/{id}/summary → stats (rows, errors, etc.)



Output ideas


•	Cleaned CSV
•	Validation report JSON
•	Error CSV (rows that failed)





6) Storage Design



Tables (minimum)


jobs

•	columns matching the core job fields above


job_artifacts (optional but clean)

•	id, jobId, kind (INPUT, OUTPUT, ERROR_REPORT)
•	storageKey or blob (choose one)
•	contentType, createdAt



Artifact storage options


•	MVP: store small files in DB as BYTEA / blob
•	Better: store files on disk (local dev) and store paths in DB
•	Later: S3/minio





7) Safety + Correctness Requirements


•	Atomic claiming (no two workers run the same job)
•	Idempotency mindset
o	each handler should tolerate re-run (or detect already-done)
•
•	Time limits (later)
o	if job runs too long → fail or mark stuck
•
•	Poison jobs
o	always failing jobs end in FAILED with error saved
•





8) Stretch Features (Add after MVP)



Platform features


•	Scheduled jobs: scheduledFor + worker only claims due jobs
•	Priority queue: higher priority jobs claimed first
•	Concurrency limits per type (e.g., only 2 CSV jobs at a time)
•	Job timeouts + heartbeat + stuck-job reaper
•	Multi-worker support with unique workerId
•	Rate limiting for submission (Redis later)



Job types you can add later (easy to extend)


•	EMAIL_SEND
•	DISCORD_WEBHOOK_POST
•	REPORT_GENERATE
•	IMAGE_RESIZE
•	DATA_IMPORT
•	WEB_SCRAPE
•	NOTIFICATION_SCHEDULE





9) “Definition of Done” Checklist (for your resume)


You are “done” when:

•	You can submit a job and get a job id back
•	Worker reliably processes jobs and updates statuses
•	Retries + maxAttempts work correctly
•	CSV job type works end-to-end (upload → process → download)
•	Logs clearly show job lifecycle
•	README explains architecture + tradeoffs + how to run both processes





